Alpha Chi National College Honor Society (or ΑΧ) is an American collegiate honor society recognizing achievements in general scholarship. It was formed in 1922 by nineteen schools in the state of Texas. Since then it has expanded to 300 chapters throughout the United States. It is an open society that invites university juniors, seniors and graduate students who are in the top 10 percent of their class into its ranks. The Daffodil Royal Court is made up of 24 senior ladies from participating Pierce County High Schools. The princesses gain many invaluable lessons and experiences throughout their year. They develop public speaking skills, tact and poise while also gaining self-confidence. They benefit from learning how to organize their time to fit everything into an incredibly tight schedule. Social development and etiquette are also taught and emphasized. They learn social graces that will enable them to always feel comfortable, because they will know what to do and how to act in any social situation. They have the opportunity to meet and interact with people of all ages, economic levels, and different lifestyles. Most importantly, they build a lifetime of beautiful memories. In 1994, the Wendy's High School Heisman (WHSH) was created to honor high school student-athletes. Each fall, the program recognizes the nation's most esteemed high-school-senior men and women for excellence in academics, athletics, and community involvement. Each school can nominate one male and one female student-athlete per year. Rotary Youth Leadership Awards (RYLA) is a leadership program coordinated by Rotary Clubs around the globe.It emphasizes training in: Fundamentals of leadership Ethics of positive leadership Importance of communication skills in effective leadership Problem-solving and conflict management Rotary's purpose and service to the community Building self-confidence and self-esteem Elements of community and global citizenship

They learn social graces that will enable them to always feel comfortable, because they will know what to do and how to act in any social situation. experience.title: Sr. Storage Systems and BDM Manager

sample_key.summary: As the Chinese saying goes, "may you live in interesting times..." Moore's law has been consistent for over 50 years now - pretty amazing in itself and most tech professionals expect it to continue - Of greater concern is how to fund ongoing acquisition of technology tools in light of financial processes that are still based on constructs from 50 years ago - that being hard assets being depreciated over the life of the asset. For buildings this is still a good idea, for IT commodities - hmmm...not so sure. The pace of innovation is extremely high wee see evidence of this in the cellular phone market where new handsets are being introduced almost every 8-9 months...at some point the cellular companies are going to offer you and me a "Service" agreement that incldues the handset and automatic upgrades when the next generation is available. Will it be slightly more expensive per month? - Yep...will it eliminate the concern and worry about migration to the latest greatest handset? Yep... You do see the handwriting on the wall - right? We are in a consumptive IT age, utilizing IT as a utility no different than the consumption method for electricity and water - do we really want to be in the business of data center (power plant) operations any longer? Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) is the next logical in technical innovation - are there issues to worry about? Of course, that's why you get paid the big bucks - make the system/services run with stability, predictability and with linear scalability, so the business can thrive. If you got this far in this summary - you see the future as we do - we should probably talk. Contact me, you will be pleasantly surprised....

projects.description: Writing policies is never easy. There are many facets and compliance issues to consider, that can make even the most enthusiastic rule setter shudder. It is by far easier for a company to stick to the status quo, not veering too far left or right of the legal minimum. That is not how I roll. Creating unique and valued benefits that enhance your team's engagement and loyalty is key to retaining talent and a personal passion of mine. Background: The PTO policy at Chums is generous, allowing up to 48 - 200 hrs/year depending on years of completed service. This, in certain cases, is not sufficient for continued income protection, especially for those who make a life on a non-professional wage. To help, I implemented a policy to allow Chums' team memebers with PTO hours to spare to donate to a "pool" for those who had exhausted their own PTO balances and still needed time off to address a serious health issue. In brief, any full-time Chums employee, who has worked a minimum of one year, can apply to the over sight committee for donated PTO. The applicant must have a documented serious health condition requiring leave from work and have exhausted all paid leave prior to application. Fairly simple. Truth be told there are some lengthy accounting calculations to be done for each donation and receipt, however, the benefits to the recipient team members far outweigh any complicated calculations that have to made to keep our Controller happy. It takes effort to discern what is going to be meaningful and valuable to your particular team. In addition, it often creates more work for HR as offering something outside the box doesn't usually come with clear instructions. Don't let that stop you from asking the questions and doing the research. Creating benefits around what your team needs can increase your employee engagement and decrease turnover both which hit the bottom line...hard.
projects.title: PTO Donation Policy

projects.description: How to develop a wellness program for a company whose employees by and large live and breathe for the outdoors? Things that make you go hmmm. Since a large percentage of our employees exercise on a regular basis outside of work I decided to explore the notion of teamwork and engagement through exercising AT work. I conducted a cursory survey to establish interest and scheduled a once/week 7 am yoga class at our Salt Lake City office and 4 pm yoga class at our Hurricane manufacturing facility. Initially both classes yielded satisfactory attendance which, predictably, declined over time. In Salt Lake the issue was 7 am and in both locations another challenge was the pull of family and outside interests impinging on "out-of-work" time. Back to the drawing board. Another survey, this time conducted face to face with each of our 65 employees to see what they were really interested in and why. The why is crucial; it allowed me to address several needs with one initiative. For instance, in one of our departments- losing weight was an ultimate goal. I attacked this from several directions and really give our employees tools the easily employ on a daily basis. We changed 25% of the snacks in our break-room vending machine, we added "Fresh Fruit Monday" and I scheduled a yoga/pilates class at noon. The class is priced (free stuff has little perceived value) at $4.00/class, substantially below what outside studios charge, and offered a 10 class punch card available for $30.00. The punch card gets "buy-in" and a certain commitment from the employee to get their moneys worth. I will expanding the program slowly and strategically with frequent employee input, measuring the results and reporting back to both team and C-level management.

experience.description: On completion the 100 Faces project will consist of 100 Portraits of Americans who have been to the theaters of war in Iraq or Afghanistan (OEF,OIF). Each portrait is accompanied by a placard featuring a statement written by the person pictured and a brief biography of the person pictured. The biographical information and the statement reflect the person at the time of the creation of the portrait. Mostly military personnel are pictured but some civilians are also pictured. All have travelled from America to the theater of war in Iraq and/or Afghanistan. The portraits are not for sale and not done at any cost to the participants. The project is being created by the artist Matt Mitchell with the help of many volunteers. Matt Mitchell selects each person to be involved and paints each portrait. The portraits and statements are meant to be exhibited both while the project is in progress and upon completion. This exhibition is meant to serve as a place where people can contemplate the nature of the American experience of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan. 100 Faces of War Experience is granted not-for-profit status nationally through New York Foundation for the Arts and locally in Western Massachusetts through the Veterans Education Project. Both organizations are 501c3 organizations.

experience.description: Headed a team responsible for writing software to encode, distribute, and track digital media assets. This included taking high volumes of media assets from customers (CDs, DVDs, music files, video files, etc), applying automated transforms, then getting them automatically imported into a distribution system for tracking and access control. The automated transforms included encoding, transcoding to different formats, and trimming to 30-second samples. The distribution system was a custom HTTP server that allowed media owners to control which digital radio stations and online retailers had access to their media. The project used agile development methods to rapidly prototype in Python against constantly changing specifications, mainly because of its similarity to C++ and extreme flexibility. Bottlenecks--for instance, the HTTP server--were rewritten in C++ for speed and efficiency. For cost efficiency reasons, the core database was Oracle which fed multiple read-only MySQL databases in the web farm. The entire project was eventually ported to run as J2EE under a BEA WebLogic server.
